    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what? lol i dont know what you mean about goblin snacks. i was just asking about business math. can u just explain the ratio thing again without the weird stuff? also how do i find the average inventory part?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, I see! You were just asking about the **Inventory Turnover Ratio** in a business math context, not the goblin snacks!\n\nThe **Inventory Turnover Ratio** is simply a measure of how efficiently you are selling your stock. It tells you how many times your entire inventory is sold and replaced over a specific period, usually a year.\n\nTo find the **Average Inventory**, you don't just take the current stock; you take the **beginning inventory** and the **ending inventory** for that period, add them together, and divide by **2**.\n\nHere is the formula:\n$$ \\text{Inventory Turnover Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)}}{\\text{Average Inventory}} $$\n\nIf your ratio is low, it means you are holding onto too much stock, which ties up cash and makes it harder to sell. If your ratio is high, it means you are moving your stock quickly.\n\nSo, to answer your specific question: **How do I find the average inventory part?** You simply add your starting inventory and your ending inventory, then divide that sum by 2.\n\nDoes that clear up the confusion?",
      "source": "target",
